re in Britain; it was once common in Yorkshire."]},{"name":"Caruth","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Cruthis","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish and northern Irish   Carruthers  . This surname is found mainly in IL and NC."]},{"name":"Cruthirds","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish and northern Irish   Carruthers  . This surname is found mainly in MS."]},{"name":"Carothers","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Caruthers","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Carruthers  ."]},{"name":"Carithers","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Carruthers  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John de Carruthers was born about 1200, in Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"Circa 1200–":"umbes 1200–Surnud","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Circa 1200":"umbes 1200","1280":"1280","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Circa 1200–":"noin 1200–Kuollut","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Circa 1200":"noin 1200","1280":"1280","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"Circa 1200–":"environ 1200–Décédé","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Circa 1200":"environ 1200","1280":"1280","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Sir John de Carruthers est né environ 1200, à Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Écosse. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Circa 1200–":"um 1200–Verstorben","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–Verstorben","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Circa 1200":"um 1200","1280":"1280","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","lifeSummary":"Sir John de Carruthers wurde um 1200 in Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"Circa 1200–":"about 1200–Desede","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–Desede","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Circa 1200":"about 1200","1280":"1280","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"hu":{"Circa 1200–":"1200 körül–elhunyt","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–elhunyt","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Circa 1200":"1200 körül","1280":"1280","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"id":{"Circa 1200–":"sekitar 1200–Telah Meninggal","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1200–Male":"1200–T